Since April last year I have been living this film. From 20 hour days with crews of 20 people on the mountain, bouncing around interviewing 20+ people to learn the history of the mountain, to working with editors to put all the pieces of the puzzle together. 

Myself, @sherpascinema and @arcteryx are excited to take you on a Rockies history lesson.

Depression is fucked. You’re judged. You’re weighed up. You’re compared to those all around you, like you, what you see, what you do, what you achieve. It is toxic, but what’s really fucked is the base line assumption we’re all starting at the same point. All even, like robots. I could go on all day about the various things that effect this, but I’m referring to and passionate about neurochemistry. I wish I wasn’t, my fixation on it is born from struggle, curiosity, pain.   Despite my vulnerability in real life and on social platforms my struggle is 99% unseen, unheard…why? Because when you’re someone like me and my brothers and sisters out there, its so constant what is the point? People hear you, people offer support, but they don’t really get it…unless they get it….and those that do are often so maxed out just dealing with their shit, fair enough. Also, those that struggle, well, ha….We are the masters of disguise - Why? Because we practice it every day….  Medication? What goes up must come down! They all have side effects, spend months, years trying to find the right one, that process? A rollercoaster of ups and downs, feeling around in the dark, floating in space, knowing you’ve well and truly lost your tether to “baseline” So…. If you’ve lost that, how do you know if you’re feeling “better” “stable” “Happy” words become meaningless when you can’t remember who you were…..  The daily come downs, oh the daily come downs…Playing poker with your dopamine levels… ill do a post fully dedicated to meds som other time.   I think in the past few years we have become a lot more aware of the struggle that is mental health and we have achieved some kind of “mass empathy” for it, but it feels really empty. Fucking empty. It’s almost worse than it was before covid.   I feel like when it was Taboo, it had some effect, some punch to it, some weight. Now it feels like it’s just another thing we pretend to acknowledge but don’t actually know how to interact with and we hear about it so much that if you don’t know, then it’s really hard to care or take seriously. Desensitized.
